FeedPackage.Description:
With service management library you can start and manage chains and contexts developed with Chains and communication services. Building up on the tcp protocol support, the "worker" and "admin" concepts are been introduced (admin as the manager process for multiple workers). All the possible actions between them are defined here, like starting, installing, uninstalling, versioning and general management. The responsible management component, the executioner, is also introduced. It is the part that starts modules using a given json configuration, coordinating admin, worker and update procedures.
(Check the examples at the project link)
Supports Mono.
FeedPackage.Tags: Distributed Scalability Administration Process-Management Tcp Http

FeedPackage.Description:
A modern, code-first, DTO-driven, web services framework encouraging best-practices development to create high-perfomance, scalable REST web services.
With a primary focus on simplicity and speed, ServiceStack allows development of web services code-first, using normal C# objects. Strong-typed DTO's provide a well-defined contract for your web service API and provides the auto-generation of documentation metadata pages, auto-configuration of popular formats (XML,JSON,HTML,CSV,JSV) and endpoints (REST,RPC,SOAP), all without any configuration or code-gen required.
Ultimately providing a clean, succinct, strong-typed API, for a friction-free development experience.

Client Side Validation can be included by inserting the following into your form:
<script src="@(CaptchaVerification.ReCaptchaJavascript)" async defer></script>
@Html.ReCaptcha()
The ReCaptcha extension method has several optional parameters to allow flexibility in rendering the ReCaptcha control.

FeedPackage.Description: This is a Scaffold extension to generate POCO class, Mapping class, Repository pattern class and DbContext. Very helpful in database-first approach without needing .edmx. Usage: On Package Manager Console type the following command: Scaffold PocoFromDB {your-connection-string} {contextName} {table name or your select query} {entityname} {providerName} Ex: Scaffold PocoFromDB "Data Source=C:\DB\Foo.sdf" FooContext Customer CustomerEntity "System.Data.SqlServerCe.4.0" Scaffold PocoFromDB "Data Source=C:\DB\Foo.sdf" FooContext "SELECT FirstName, LastName FROM Customer" CustomerEntity "System.Data.SqlServerCe.4.0" Special Note: If your connection string contains special character/reserve for PowerShell such as '$', you need escape it with '`' character. Example: pa$$word01 will be pa`$`$word01
